
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `foo2lava-wrapper` baraye tabdil file-haye chap shode (print jobs) az format Foo2lava be format-i ke printer-haye PostScript mitavanand befahmand estefade mishavad. In dastoor, yek vasete (wrapper) ast ke be printer ezafe mishavad ta kare chap ra asan konad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-z[0-9]`  --> 📏 Tarife sathe compression baraye kam kardane حجم فایل
    🔹 `-b <bits>`  --> 🎨 Tarife تعداد bits per pixel
    🔹 `-r <dpi>`   --> 🎯 Tarife daqate chap (dots per inch)

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ foo2lava-wrapper -r600 -z5 file.prn > file.ps

    🔹 Tabdil file.prn ba daqate 600 DPI va compression level 5 be file.ps

    $ foo2lava-wrapper file.prn | lpr

    🔹 Chap kardane file.prn be soorate mostaqim az tarighe command lpr

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ foo2lava-wrapper -b1 file.prn > file.ps

    🔹 Tabdil file.prn ba yek bit per pixel va save kardane output be file.ps. In معمولاً baraye chap-haye سیاه و سفید (black and white) be kar miravad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `foo2lava-wrapper` command is used to convert print jobs from the Foo2lava format to a format understandable by PostScript printers. This command acts as a wrapper, added to printers to simplify printing tasks.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-z[0-9]`  --> 📏 Defines the compression level to reduce file size
    🔹 `-b <bits>`  --> 🎨 Defines the number of bits per pixel
    🔹 `-r <dpi>`   --> 🎯 Defines the print resolution (dots per inch)

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ foo2lava-wrapper -r600 -z5 file.prn > file.ps

    🔹 Converts file.prn with a resolution of 600 DPI and compression level 5 to file.ps

    $ foo2lava-wrapper file.prn | lpr

    🔹 Prints file.prn directly using the lpr command

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ foo2lava-wrapper -b1 file.prn > file.ps

    🔹 Converts file.prn with one bit per pixel and saves the output to file.ps. This is typically used for black and white prints.

